{{Infobox terrorist attack |title=2007 Algiers bombings |image=Algiers location.svg |caption= |location=[[Algiers]], [[Algeria]] |target=[[United Nations]], Constitutional Court |date=11 December 2007 |time=09:30 |timezone=GMT+1 |type=[[suicide bombing]]s |fatalities=41 (incl. 17 UN staff)<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/reuters/2008/03/09/africa/OUKWD-UK-ALGERIA-QAEDA-DENIAL.php Qaeda in north Africa says kills 20 Algeria troops - International Herald Tribune<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> |injuries=170 |perps=claimed by [[al-Qaeda Organization in the Islamic Maghreb]] }}
There were two near simultaneous '''bombings in Algiers''' which occurred on 11 December 2007 when two [[car bomb]]s exploded 10 minutes apart starting at around 9:30 a.m. local time, in the [[Algeria]]n capital [[Algiers]].<ref name="CBC">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2007/12/11/algeria.html|title=11 UN workers among 26 killed in Algeria blasts|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=2007-12-11|accessdate=2007-12-12}}</ref> The [[al-Qaeda Organization in the Islamic Maghreb]] has claimed responsibility for the attacks, stating that it was "another successful conquest […] carried out by the Knights of the Faith with their blood in defense of the wounded nation of Islam."<ref name="CBC"/><ref name="Al Jazeera - Al Qaeda statement">{{cite news |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/4371B609-73CB-4AA2-8CC5-308B7C4092C7.htm |title=Al-Qaeda claims Algeria bombings |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=2007-12-12 |accessdate=2007-12-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080401075350/http://english.aljazeera.net/NR/exeres/4371B609-73CB-4AA2-8CC5-308B7C4092C7.htm |archivedate=2008-04-01 |df= }}</ref> These attacks constitute another act of violence in the ongoing [[Islamic insurgency in Algeria (2002–present)|Islamic insurgency]], a continuation of the [[Algerian Civil War]] that has claimed 200,000 lives.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.aljazeera.net/English/archive/archive?ArchiveId=9739 |title=Algeria puts strife toll at 150,000 |publisher=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=2005-02-25 |accessdate=2007-12-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214091507/http://english.aljazeera.net/English/archive/archive?ArchiveId=9739 |archivedate=2007-12-14 |df= }} Note that the 150,000 figure was given on February 2005, and the Reuters article from June 2007 (below) includes an updated figure of 200,000 casualties.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSL04297301|title=Algeria violence death toll at year low in May|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=2007-06-04|accessdate=2007-12-12}}</ref>
==Targets== Two [[car bombs]] containing 800&nbsp;kg (1,700&nbsp;lb) of explosives each were used in the bombings.<ref name="bbc_unreview">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/7139787.stm|title=UN review after Algiers bombing |publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=2007-12-11|accessdate=2007-12-12}}</ref> The first explosion occurred in the Ben Aknoun district, near the Supreme Constitutional Court. This was followed ten minutes later by a second blast on the road that separates the [[United Nations]] offices from the offices of the [[UNHCR]] (United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees) in the Hydra neighborhood.<ref name="UNHCR">{{cite news|url=http://www.unhcr.org/news/NEWS/475ebc454.html|title=UNHCR chief condemns Algiers bombing; mourns dead|publisher=[[UNHCR]]|date=2007-12-11|accessdate=2007-12-12}}</ref> The United Nations building partially collapsed in the explosion while the UNHCR offices were "leveled" according to a UNHCR official.<ref name="CNN2" /> The United Nations building housed the offices of the [[UNDP|UN Development Programme]] (UNDP), the [[World Food Programme]] (WFP), the [[International Labour Organization]] (ILO), the [[UN Industrial Development Organization]] (UNIDO), the [[UNAIDS|Joint UN Programme on HIV/AIDS]] (UNAIDS), the Department of Safety and Security (DSS) and the [[UNFPA|Population Fund]] (UNFPA).<ref name="AP1">{{cite news|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gkGPT-k67MF4UR_s90Y_CNnZJkgQD8TFMKPO0 |title=UN in Grief at Algeria Bombings |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=2007-12-12 |accessdate=2007-12-12 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071214163944/http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5gkGPT-k67MF4UR_s90Y_CNnZJkgQD8TFMKPO0 |archivedate=December 14, 2007 }}</ref> The collapsed section mainly housed the UNDP.<ref name="bbc_unreview" />
The attack against the UN office was a suicide bombing.<ref name="bbc_unreview" /> It is as yet unknown whether the same is true for the Constitutional Court attack.
The attack caused the third highest staff casualties in the history of the United Nations, after the 2003 [[Canal Hotel bombing]], which targeted the UN headquarters in [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]] and also killed the Secretary-General's Special Representative to Iraq [[Sérgio Vieira de Mello]] and 21 other staff members<ref name="CBC"/> and the [[2010 Haiti earthquake]] in which 22 UN peacekeepers have been confirmed dead as of January 14, 2010; and 150 missing. The [[Hédi Annabi|Head]] of [[MINUSTAH]] was killed in the disaster.
{{Campaignbox Algeria 2002-present}}
==Casualties== {| class="wikitable centre sortable" |+ Deaths by nationality !Country !Number |- | {{flagu|Algeria}} ! 37+ |- | {{flagu|Denmark}} ! 1 |- | {{flagu|Philippines}} ! 1 |- | {{flagu|Senegal}} ! 1 |- | {{flagu|China}} ! 1 |- |- class="sortbottom" |'''Total''' ! 41+ |}
{{Update|inaccurate=yes|date=December 2012}} The bombings are believed to have killed at least 31 people. Among the dead were 17 United Nations employees at work in their offices, including 14 Algerians and a [[Denmark|Dane]], a [[Philippines|Filipino]], and a [[Senegal]]ese.<ref name="AP">{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071214/ap_on_re_af/algeria_bombing |title=UN death toll in Algeria raised to 17 |publisher=[[Associated Press]] |date=2007-12-14 |accessdate=2007-12-14 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071216115256/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071214/ap_on_re_af/algeria_bombing |archivedate=2007-12-16 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> A [[China|Chinese]] construction worker was also killed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://english.zjol.com.cn/05english/system/2007/12/13/009050763.shtml |title=Chinese company sends mission to Algeria to mourn bombing victim |publisher=[[Xinhua]] |date=2007-12-13 |accessdate=2007-12-14 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215074006/http://english.zjol.com.cn/05english/system/2007/12/13/009050763.shtml |archivedate=2007-12-15 |df= }}</ref> This official death toll, provided by Algerian [[Interior Minister]] [[Yazid Zerhouni]], conflicts with numbers reported by hospital and rescue officials, which triple the government's count.<ref name="CBC"/><ref name="CNN2">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2007/WORLD/africa/12/11/algeria.blast/index.html?iref=mpstoryview|title=Rescuers search for bomb survivors|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=2007-12-12|accessdate=2007-12-12}}</ref>
Many people are still unaccounted for. A number of them are possibly still trapped under the rubble, according to UN spokeswoman Maria Okabe. Jean Fabre, head of the UN Development Programme's [[Geneva]] office, indicated they were still searching for survivors in the rubble.<ref name="CBC"/>
177 people were injured in total, according to Zerhouni.<ref name="CBC"/> [[CNN]] has confirmed that the bombers used homemade [[nitroglycerin]] bombs, which had iron nails in them to increase casualties.<ref name="CBC"/>
The [[United Nations Security Council]] held an official meeting on the same day in order to condemn the attacks.<ref name="UN_SPV5798_2007">{{UN document |docid=S-PV-5798 |date=11 December 2007 |type=Verbatim Report |body=Security Council |meeting=5798 |accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref>
