[[File:330 Sussex Ottawa Facade.JPG|thumb|right|Current home of the Global Centre for Pluralism on Sussex Drive, Ottawa.]]
The '''Global Centre for Pluralism''' ({{lang-fr|'''Centre mondial du pluralisme'''}}) is an international centre for research, education and exchange about the values, practices and policies that underpin [[Pluralism (political philosophy)|pluralist societies]].<ref name="PRAKDN20061025">{{cite press release |title=Government of Canada and Aga Khan Sign Funding Agreement for Global Centre for Pluralism |publisher=[[Aga Khan Development Network]] |date=2006-10-25 |url=http://www.akdn.org/news/2006Oct25.html |accessdate=2007-04-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070506071433/http://www.akdn.org/news/2006Oct25.html |archivedate=2007-05-06 |df= }}</ref> Based in [[Ottawa|Ottawa, Ontario]], Canada, the Centre seeks to assist the creation of successful societies and was founded on the premise that tolerance, openness and understanding towards the cultures, social structures, values and faiths of other peoples are now essential to the survival of an interdependent world.

The Global Centre for Pluralism is an international initiative of [[Aga Khan IV]], 49th hereditary Imam of [[Ismaili|Ismaili Muslims]], and was established jointly with the [[Government of Canada]] in 2006.<ref name="PRAKDN20050418">{{cite press release
 |title       = Aga Khan welcomes Government of Canada's partnership in new Global Centre for Pluralism
 |url         = http://www.akdn.org/news/2005April18.htm
 |publisher   = [[Aga Khan Development Network]]
 |date        = 2005-04-18
 |accessdate  = 2007-04-06
 |deadurl     = yes
 |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070404091238/http://www.akdn.org/news/2005April18.htm
 |archivedate = 2007-04-04
 |df          = 
}}</ref> It is located in the former [[Canadian War Museum]] building along Ottawa's [[Sussex Drive]] and was officially opened on May 16, 2017.<ref>{{cite press release
 | title      = Official Opening of the Global Centre for Pluralism’s international headquarters
 | url        = http://www.pluralism.ca/en/events/official-opening.html
 | publisher  = Global Centre for Pluralism
 | date       = 2017-05-16
 | accessdate = 2007-07-07
}}</ref> The Centre draws inspiration from the Canadian experience<ref name="PRAKDN20061025"/> and functions as a global repository and a source of knowledge and know-how about fostering pluralistic values, policies, and practices. It aims to work with countries to nurture successful civil societies in which every citizen, irrespective of cultural, religious or ethnic differences, is able to realize his or her full potential.

==Board of directors==
The Board of Directors of the Global Centre for Pluralism gathered for their inaugural meeting in Ottawa from October 7&ndash;8, 2010.<ref name="TIO20101007">{{cite news |title=Mawlana Hazar Imam arrives in Ottawa for inaugural Global Centre for Pluralism board meeting |publisher=TheIsmaili.org |date=2010-10-07 |url=http://www.theismaili.org/cms/1097/Mawlana-Hazar-Imam-arrives-in-Ottawa-for-inaugural-Global-Centre-for-Pluralism-board-meeting |accessdate=2010-10-07}}</ref> Composed of renowned Canadian and international leaders and thinkers, the Board includes the following members:<ref name="PRAKFC20101007"/>
* '''[[Aga Khan IV|His Highness the Aga Khan]]''', (''Chairman of the Board'') Founder and Chairman of the [[Aga Khan Development Network]] (AKDN) and 49th hereditary Imam of the [[Ismaili|Shia Ismaili Muslims]];
* '''[[Zahra Aga Khan|Princess Zahra Aga Khan]]''', Head of the AKDN's Social Welfare department;
* '''[[Kofi Annan]]''', former [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]];
* '''[[Iain Benson]]''', Canadian lawyer and Professor of Law at the [[University of the Free State]] in [[Bloemfontein]];
* '''[[Adrienne Clarkson|The Right Honourable Adrienne Clarkson]]''', former [[Governor General of Canada]];
* '''[[Rudyard Griffiths]]''', co-founder of the [[Dominion Institute]];
* '''[[Huguette Labelle]]''', Chancellor of the [[University of Ottawa]];
* '''[[Azim Nanji]]''', Senior Associate Director for the [[Abbasi Program in Islamic Studies]] at [[Stanford University]];
* '''Margaret Ogilvie''', Chancellor's Professor of Law, [[Carleton University]];
* '''Khalil Shariff''', Chief Executive Officer of the [[Aga Khan Foundation|Aga Khan Foundation Canada]] and
* '''[[Eduardo Stein]]''', diplomat and former [[Vice President of Guatemala|Vice President]] of [[Guatemala]].

==Building==
[[File:Dominion Archives 1923.jpg|thumb|The building in 1923]]
{{Commonscat-inline|Former Archives Building}}

When fully operational, the Global Centre for Pluralism will be located at 330 Sussex Drive in Ottawa,<ref name="PRAKFC20101007">{{Cite press release | title = GLOBAL CENTRE FOR PLURALISM HOLDS INAUGURAL BOARD MEETING | publisher = Aga Khan Foundation Canada | date = 2010-10-07 | url = http://www.newswire.ca/en/releases/archive/October2010/07/c9080.html | accessdate = 2010-10-07}}</ref> a building that served as the home of the [[Library and Archives Canada|Public Archives of Canada]] from 1906 to 1967 and the [[Canadian War Museum]] from 1967 to 2005. The building was built from 1904 to 1906 and is designated a [[National Historic Site of Canada]] and a [[Classified Federal Heritage Building]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historicplaces.ca/visit-visite/affichage-display.aspx?id%3D3462 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224032107/http://www.historicplaces.ca/visit-visite/affichage-display.aspx?id=3462 |archivedate=2012-02-24 |df= }}Canadian Register of Historic Places.</ref>

The building has been vacant for several years and requires significant renovation and rehabilitation.<ref name="PRAKFC20101007"/> A multi-phased revitalization of the heritage property is currently underway.<ref name="PRAKFC20101007"/>

== Profile of activities ==
The Global Centre for Pluralism draws on Canada’s successful record in constructing and sustaining pluralist [[civil society]]. Working closely with governments, academia and civil society around the world, the Centre is a think-tank for studying and fostering pluralism.<ref name="OttawaCitizen20061027">{{cite news |url=http://www.canada.com/globaltv/ontario/story.html?id=d6064d7f-68d2-47d1-91e8-b723aea08af3&k=37878 |title=Muslim leader plays down 'clash of civilizations' |last=Zabjek |first=Alexandra |publisher=CanWest News Service |work=The Ottawa Citizen |date=2006-10-27 |accessdate=2007-04-05 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024212632/http://www.canada.com/globaltv/ontario/story.html?id=d6064d7f-68d2-47d1-91e8-b723aea08af3&k=37878 |archivedate=2012-10-24 |df= }}</ref> It seeks to foster legislation and policy that strengthens developing countries’ capacity for enhancing pluralism in law, justice, the arts, the media, financial services, health and education. In addition, it will deliver programs, facilitate dialogue, develop pedagogical materials and work with partners worldwide to build capacity to promote indigenous approaches to pluralism within countries and communities.<ref name="PRAKDN20050418"/>

From its inception, the Centre is expected to be one of the largest think-tanks in Canada.<ref name="OttawaCitizen20040521">{{cite news | url=http://ismaili.net/timeline/2004/20040521oc.html |title=Aga Khan announces think-tank for Ottawa | date=2004-05-21 | publisher=The Ottawa Citizen |last=Singer |first=Zev |accessdate=2007-04-06}}</ref> Its mission is consistent with Canadian international policy objectives, including the promotion of democracy and good governance, a more equitable sharing of the world’s resources between developed and developing countries, and the projection of Canadian values, such as the rule of law, human rights and respect for diversity.<ref name="PRAKDN20050418"/>

The Centre honours people, for efforts to build an inclusive society, with the Global Pluralism Awards. The awards were presented for the first time on November 15, 2017, with the winners being Leyner Palacios Asprilla of Colombia, Alice Wairimu Nderitu of Kenya, and Daniel Webb of Australia.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Farooqui |first1=Salmaan |author-link1= |title=Inclusion in action: Meet the three winners of the Global Pluralism Awards |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/inclusion-in-action-meet-the-three-winners-of-the-global-pluralismawards/article36971550/ |dead-url=no |department= |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |type=newspaper |issue= |publication-date=November 14, 2017 (online) and November 15, 2017 (in print newspaper) |pages=A8-A9 (print) |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127171311/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/inclusion-in-action-meet-the-three-winners-of-the-global-pluralismawards/article36971550/ |archive-date=November 27, 2017 |access-date=March 19, 2018 |quote= |ref= }}</ref>

